# ============================================================================
# 1. PROJECT ARCHITECTURE AND STRUCTURE
# ============================================================================

## 1.1 System Overview
- This is a **dual-pipeline Electronic Warfare system**:
  - **ED Pipeline (Electronic Support)**: Signal detection, parameter extraction, monitoring, direction finding, geolocation
  - **ET Pipeline (Electronic Attack)**: Jamming, spoofing, deception operations
- The system operates in **real-time** with **multi-threaded** processing
- All modules are **independent libraries** that can be integrated together
- Hardware: HackRF One SDR with 4-antenna circular array for direction finding

## 1.2 Module Structure
The project is organized into modules following this pattern:
```
4.X_ModuleName/
├── include/               # Public header files (.hpp)
│   ├── DataStructures.hpp # Module-specific data structures
│   ├── ModuleEngine.hpp   # Core processing engine
│   └── ModulePipeline.hpp # Thread-safe pipeline orchestrator
├── src/                   # Implementation files (.cpp)
│   ├── ModuleEngine.cpp
│   └── ModulePipeline.cpp
├── examples/              # Example usage programs
│   └── example_usage.cpp
├── CMakeLists.txt         # Build configuration
├── README.md              # Module documentation
├── MODULE_SUMMARY.md      # Technical summary (if exists)
├── NASIL_CALISTIRILIR.md  # How to run (Turkish)
└── *.txt                  # Technical specifications
```

## 1.3 Existing Modules Status
- **4.1 Sinyal Tespiti**: Signal detection (partial implementation, SinyalTespit.cpp exists)
- **4.2 Parametre Çıkarımı**: ✅ **PRODUCTION READY** - Hybrid AI+DSP parameter extraction
- **4.3 Sinyal İzleme-Dinleme**: ✅ **PRODUCTION READY** - Signal monitoring and demodulation
- **4.4 Yön Bulma (DF)**: ✅ **PRODUCTION READY** - Direction finding with pseudo-Doppler
- **4.5 Konum Belirleme**: Geolocation (specification only, needs implementation)
- **5.1-5.4 ET Modules**: Electronic attack modules (specifications exist, need implementation)

## 1.4 Module Dependencies
```
4.1 (Detection) → 4.2 (Parameter Extraction) → 4.3 (Monitoring) → 4.4 (Direction Finding) → 4.5 (Geolocation)
                                                                  ↓
                                              5.X (Electronic Attack Modules)
```

# ============================================================================
# 2. C++ STANDARDS AND CODING CONVENTIONS
# ============================================================================

## 2.1 Language Standard
- **ALWAYS use C++17** (CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD 17)
- **NEVER use C++20/23 features** (project compatibility requirement)
- Standard library only, no Boost unless absolutely necessary

## 2.2 Compiler Requirements
- **Primary compiler**: GCC 7+ or Clang 5+
- **Compiler flags (mandatory)**:
  ```cmake
  set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS} -Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic")
  set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_DEBUG "-g -O0 -DDEBUG")
  set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_RELEASE "-O3 -DNDEBUG -march=native")
  ```
- All code must compile **without warnings** on `-Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic`

## 2.3 Naming Conventions
- **Namespaces**: `CognitiveRF`, `CognitiveRF::ModuleName`
  ```cpp
  namespace CognitiveRF {
  namespace SignalMonitoring {
      // code here
  }}
  ```
- **Classes**: PascalCase (e.g., `ModulationClassifier`, `DirectionFindingEngine`)
- **Functions/Methods**: camelCase (e.g., `processBuffer`, `computeRSSI`)
- **Variables**: snake_case (e.g., `sample_rate_hz`, `center_freq`)
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `MAX_BUFFER_SIZE`)
- **Member variables**: snake_case with trailing underscore (e.g., `sample_rate_hz_`, `running_`)
- **Enums**: PascalCase with UPPER_CASE values
  ```cpp
  enum class ModulationType : uint8_t {
      UNKNOWN = 0,
      BPSK,
      QPSK
  };
  ```

## 2.4 File Organization
- **Header files**: `.hpp` extension (NOT `.h`)
- **Implementation files**: `.cpp` extension
- **Include guards**: Use `#ifndef/#define/#endif` (NOT `#pragma once`)
  ```cpp
  #ifndef MODULE_NAME_HPP
  #define MODULE_NAME_HPP
  // content
  #endif
  ```
- **Header order**:
  1. Own header (for .cpp files)
  2. C++ standard library headers
  3. Third-party library headers
  4. Project headers

# ============================================================================
# 3. DEPENDENCIES AND BUILD SYSTEM
# ============================================================================

## 3.1 Required Dependencies
- **Threads**: `find_package(Threads REQUIRED)` - For multi-threading
- **ONNX Runtime**: AI modulation classification (4.2 module)
- **SQLite3**: Persistence logging (4.2 module)
- **FFTW3**: Optional, for FFT operations (Welch PSD)
- **liquid-dsp**: Optional, for production demodulation
- **libhackrf**: For SDR hardware communication

## 3.2 CMake Build Structure
Every module MUST have a CMakeLists.txt with:
```cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.15)
project(CognitiveRF_ModuleName VERSION 1.0.0 LANGUAGES CXX)

set(CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD 17)
set(CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD_REQUIRED ON)
set(CMAKE_CXX_EXTENSIONS OFF)

# Compiler flags
set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS} -Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic")
set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_DEBUG "-g -O0 -DDEBUG")
set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_RELEASE "-O3 -DNDEBUG -march=native")

# Dependencies
find_package(Threads REQUIRED)
# ... other dependencies

# Source files
set(HEADER_FILES include/*.hpp)
set(SOURCE_FILES src/*.cpp)

# Library target
add_library(${PROJECT_NAME} STATIC ${HEADER_FILES} ${SOURCE_FILES})
target_include_directories(${PROJECT_NAME}
    PUBLIC
        $<BUILD_INTERFACE:${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/include>
        $<INSTALL_INTERFACE:include>
)
target_link_libraries(${PROJECT_NAME} PUBLIC Threads::Threads)

# Example executable (optional)
option(BUILD_EXAMPLES "Build example programs" ON)
if(BUILD_EXAMPLES)
    add_executable(example_usage examples/example_usage.cpp)
    target_link_libraries(example_usage PRIVATE ${PROJECT_NAME})
endif()
```

## 3.3 Conditional Compilation
Use preprocessor definitions for optional dependencies:
```cpp
#ifdef ONNXRUNTIME_AVAILABLE
    // ONNX-specific code
#endif

#ifdef USE_LIQUID_DSP
    // liquid-dsp code
#endif
```

# ============================================================================
# 4. DATA STRUCTURES AND TYPES
# ============================================================================

## 4.1 Standard Data Structures
Every module MUST have a `DataStructures.hpp` file defining:
- **Enums**: Signal classification (ModulationType, ProtocolType, SignalClass)
- **Structs**: Data containers with clear member documentation
- **Type aliases**: For clarity (e.g., `using IQSample = std::complex<float>`)

## 4.2 Core Data Types
- **Frequency**: `uint64_t` or `double` in Hz (NOT MHz/GHz)
- **Sample rate**: `uint32_t` or `double` in samples per second
- **Power levels**: `float` in dBm
- **IQ samples**: `std::vector<std::complex<float>>`
- **Timestamps**: `uint64_t` in milliseconds or nanoseconds
- **Angles**: `float` or `double` in degrees (NOT radians in public API)

## 4.3 Configuration Structures
Use configuration structs with sensible defaults:
```cpp
struct PipelineConfig {
    double sample_rate_hz = 20e6;
    float noise_floor_dbm = -100.0f;
    bool enable_tracking = true;
    // ... other options
};
```

# ============================================================================
# 5. THREADING AND CONCURRENCY
# ============================================================================

## 5.1 Thread-Safe Queue Pattern
**MANDATORY** for all pipeline modules:
```cpp
template<typename T>
class ThreadSafeQueue {
private:
    std::queue<T> queue_;
    mutable std::mutex mutex_;
    std::condition_variable cond_var_;
    bool shutdown_ = false;

public:
    void push(const T& item);
    bool pop(T& item);  // Blocking
    bool try_pop(T& item);  // Non-blocking
    void shutdown();
};
```

## 5.2 Pipeline Pattern
All processing modules MUST follow this pattern:
```cpp
class ModulePipeline {
public:
    explicit ModulePipeline(const PipelineConfig& config);
    void start();  // Start processing thread
    void stop();   // Stop gracefully
    bool submitData(const InputData& data);  // Thread-safe input
    bool getResult(OutputData& result);      // Thread-safe output
    void setResultCallback(std::function<void(const OutputData&)> callback);

private:
    void processingLoop();  // Main thread function
    std::atomic<bool> running_{false};
    std::thread processing_thread_;
    ThreadSafeQueue<InputData> input_queue_;
    ThreadSafeQueue<OutputData> output_queue_;
};
```

## 5.3 Thread Safety Rules
- **ALWAYS** use `std::atomic<bool>` for state flags (e.g., `running_`, `shutdown_`)
- **ALWAYS** use `std::mutex` to protect shared data
- **NEVER** use raw mutex locks, use RAII (`std::lock_guard`, `std::unique_lock`)
- **ALWAYS** use condition variables for efficient blocking waits
- For HackRF state management, use `std::atomic::compare_exchange_strong` to prevent race conditions

## 5.4 Threading Model
Standard threading architecture:
- **Thread-1 (Hardware Sweep)**: HackRF RX Capture + Queue Push
- **Thread-2 (DSP Engine)**: Queue Pop + Signal Processing + GMM
- **Thread-3 (Tracking)**: Signal tracking + CFO correction
- **Thread-4 (Direction Finding)**: RF switch control + AoA calculation
- **Thread-5 (Geo-Location)**: Cross-station data fusion
- **Thread-6 (AI Inference)**: ONNX modulation classification
- **Thread-7 (Demodulation)**: liquid-dsp processing
- **Thread-8 (UI & Logging)**: Visualization and database

# ============================================================================
# 6. SIGNAL PROCESSING ALGORITHMS
# ============================================================================

## 6.1 Welch PSD Implementation
- **Window function**: Hamming window
- **Overlap**: 50%
- **FFT size**: 1024 or 2048
- **Library**: FFTW3 (if available) or fallback FFT
```cpp
// Welch PSD formula:
// P_Welch(k) = (1/M) * sum_{m=0}^{M-1} |FFT{x_m(n) * w(n)}|^2
```

## 6.2 Kalman Filter for CFO Tracking
State vector: `[CFO, CFO_rate]`
```cpp
// Predict:
// X_predict(k) = A * X(k-1)
// P_predict(k) = A * P(k-1) * A^T + Q

// Update:
// K(k) = P_predict(k) * H^T * [H * P_predict(k) * H^T + R]^-1
// X(k) = X_predict(k) + K(k) * [Z(k) - H * X_predict(k)]
// P(k) = [I - K(k) * H] * P_predict(k)
```

## 6.3 Frequency Correction
**Complex frequency shift formula**:
```cpp
x_corrected(n) = x_raw(n) * exp(-j * 2 * PI * CFO * n / SAMPLE_RATE)
```

## 6.4 FM Demodulation (Frequency Discriminator)
```cpp
// Phase difference method:
// phase[n] = atan2(imag(x[n] * conj(x[n-1])), real(x[n] * conj(x[n-1])))
// audio[n] = phase[n] / (2 * PI)
```

## 6.5 AM Demodulation (Envelope Detector)
```cpp
// y[n] = sqrt(I^2[n] + Q^2[n])
```

# ============================================================================
# 7. AI/ML INTEGRATION (Module 4.2)
# ============================================================================

## 7.1 ONNX Runtime Usage
- **Model format**: ONNX (.onnx)
- **Inference library**: ONNX Runtime C++ API
- **Input tensor**: `float[2][1024]` (I and Q channels)
- **Output**: 14-class modulation classification

## 7.2 IQ Preprocessing Pipeline
**MANDATORY** preprocessing before AI inference:
```cpp
// Step A: DC Removal
I_new = I - mean(I);
Q_new = Q - mean(Q);

// Step B: Local Z-Score Normalization
I_norm = (I_new - mean(I_new)) / (std(I_new) + 1e-8);
Q_norm = (Q_new - mean(Q_new)) / (std(Q_new) + 1e-8);

// Step C: Optional Clipping
clip(value, -4.0f, 4.0f);
```

## 7.3 Temporal Voting
Implement N-frame majority voting:
```cpp
std::deque<ModulationType> voting_history_;
// Store last N predictions
// Return most frequent prediction as final result
// Compute confidence: confidence = votes / total_votes
```

## 7.4 Model Performance Expectations
- SNR > 10 dB: ~95% accuracy
- SNR 0-10 dB: ~87% accuracy
- SNR -5-0 dB: ~63% accuracy
- SNR < -5 dB: ~21% accuracy

# ============================================================================
# 8. HARDWARE INTERFACE (HackRF One)
# ============================================================================

## 8.1 HackRF Specifications
- **Frequency range**: 1 MHz - 6 GHz
- **Sample rate**: 20 MSPS (20e6 Hz)
- **Bandwidth**: 20 MHz
- **Mode**: Half-duplex (NOT full-duplex)
- **Library**: libhackrf

## 8.2 Hardware State Management
Use atomic state machine for RX/TX switching:
```cpp
enum class HardwareState {
    IDLE,
    SENSING,  // RX mode
    JAMMING,  // TX mode
    SPOOFING  // TX mode (GNSS)
};

std::atomic<HardwareState> hw_state_{HardwareState::IDLE};

// Safe state transition:
HardwareState expected = HardwareState::IDLE;
hw_state_.compare_exchange_strong(expected, HardwareState::SENSING);
```

## 8.3 Frequency Sweep Parameters
- **Start frequency**: 1 MHz (1e6 Hz)
- **End frequency**: 6 GHz (6e9 Hz)
- **Step**: 10 MHz (10e6 Hz)
- **Settling time**: 40 ms (for PLL lock)

## 8.4 Gain Settings
- **LNA gain**: 24-32 dB
- **VGA gain**: 16-24 dB
- **AMP**: OFF (for RX), ON (for TX if needed)

# ============================================================================
# 9. DIRECTION FINDING (Module 4.4)
# ============================================================================

## 9.1 Antenna Array Configuration
- **Type**: 4-element circular array
- **Spacing**: λ/2 at target frequency
- **Switching pattern**: [0, 1, 2, 3, 0, 1, 2, 3, ...]
- **Switching rate**: kHz range

## 9.2 Pseudo-Doppler Algorithm
```cpp
// FM discriminator demodulation
phase[n] = atan2(imag(x[n] * conj(x[n-1])), real(x[n] * conj(x[n-1])));

// Phase unwrapping
phase_unwrapped = unwrapPhase(phase, prev_phase);

// Phase to AoA conversion (4-element array)
AoA = phase_difference * (90.0 / (2 * PI));  // degrees
```

## 9.3 Performance Requirements
- **RMS accuracy**: ±10° (target)
- **AoA range**: -180° to +180°
- **Confidence**: SNR-based (0.0 - 1.0)

# ============================================================================
# 10. GEOLOCATION (Module 4.5)
# ============================================================================

## 10.1 Cross-Fixing Method
- **Minimum stations**: 2
- **Algorithm**: Least Squares optimization
- **Input**: AoA from each station + GPS coordinates
- **Output**: Target latitude/longitude + error ellipse

## 10.2 Data Synchronization
- **Time sync**: GPS/GNSS timestamps (ms precision)
- **Data link**: Wireless/network between stations
- **Format**: Compact data packets with AoA + timestamp + station ID

# ============================================================================
# 11. ELECTRONIC ATTACK MODULES (5.1-5.4)
# ============================================================================

## 11.1 Spot Jamming (5.1)
- **Type**: Continuous wave (CW) or Gaussian noise
- **Bandwidth**: Match target signal
- **Power**: Maximize SNR disruption
- **Frequency**: 0-3 GHz

## 11.2 Look-Through Jamming (5.2)
- **Mode**: Time-Division Duplex (TDD)
- **RX window**: ~10 ms (sensing)
- **TX window**: 50-100 ms (jamming)
- **State machine**: IDLE ↔ SENSING ↔ JAMMING

## 11.3 GNSS Spoofing (5.4)
- **Services**: GPS L1 (1575.42 MHz), GLONASS L1, Galileo E1
- **Method**: Real-time I/Q synthesis + power-managed alignment
- **Power strategy**: Start low, gradually increase
- **Doppler**: Apply frequency shift for motion simulation

# ============================================================================
# 12. ERROR HANDLING AND LOGGING
# ============================================================================

## 12.1 Error Handling Strategy
- Use **exceptions** for unrecoverable errors
- Use **return codes** (bool/int) for operational errors
- **NEVER** use exceptions in real-time processing loops
- Provide detailed error messages with context

## 12.2 Logging Levels
```cpp
enum class LogLevel {
    DEBUG,    // Verbose debugging
    INFO,     // General information
    WARNING,  // Potential issues
    ERROR,    // Recoverable errors
    CRITICAL  // System failure
};
```

## 12.3 Performance Logging
Track and log:
- Processing time per signal (ms)
- Queue sizes (input/output)
- Thread utilization
- Memory usage
- Hardware state transitions

